In Finland, a law will enter into force on Tuesday that limits the acquisition of substances suitable for the manufacture of explosives.
In the future, private individuals will have to apply for a permit from the Police Board in order to buy or possess substances or mixtures that could be used as the so-called starting material for explosives.
Such substances include hydrogen peroxide, nitromethane, nitric acid, potassium chlorate, potassium perchlorate, sodium chlorate and sodium perchlorate, as well as mixtures containing them, if the specified concentration values are exceeded.
Hydrogen peroxide is, for example, in cleaning and washing agents, but the concentrations in them usually do not exceed the limit values.
Nitromethane is used, for example, in acceleration driving.
Starting materials acquired before the entry into force of the law may, however, be kept and used until March 2, 2016.
