The researchers reviewed the women&#39;s health history over a period of seven years.
According to doctor Susan Jordan, a woman&#39;s age at the time of diagnosis, type of ovarian cancer, previous illnesses and socioeconomic status also affected the chance of survival.
Older women and when the cancer had spread more widely at the time of diagnosis had the lowest probability of survival.
Women living in sparsely populated and remote areas were 20 percent more likely to die during the study than women living in urban areas.
The study did not try to find out why women living outside the cities have a lower chance of surviving ovarian cancer, but Jordan considers delayed diagnosis and difficult access to treatment as possible reasons.
&quot;Gynecologic oncology specialists treat this disease best, and their practices are mostly located in big cities,&quot; says Jordan.
