A genetic abnormality is often misdiagnosed
For years, a British woman feared death because of a wrong diagnosis.
For most of her youth, Karin Rodgers thought she only had a few years left to live because she had been diagnosed with another disease.
Actually, he suffered from Charcot-Marie-Tooth disease (CMT). It refers to a group of inherited diseases that damage nerves outside the brain and spinal cord.
According to Charity CMT UK, misdiagnosis is a common problem with CMT cases because so little is known about them.
It is estimated that around 23,000 people in the UK suffer from CMT, which causes motor symptoms such as muscle weakness, difficulty walking and tingling in the toes.
The disease can also cause numbness or pain, and is incurable and progressive, meaning symptoms get worse over time.
When Rodgers was 13, he thought he had Friedreich&#39;s ataxia (FA), which has a really poor survival rate.
Rodgers believed he would be confined to a wheelchair before he turned 18 and die before he reached the age of 30.
Today, the 51-year-old mother of two says that &quot;as a child, I knew I couldn&#39;t do the same things as others.
I fell every day and it took me longer than others in everything.
I could never roller skate or skateboard with the other kids, and I was bullied at school because I walked and ran differently than the others.
When Rodgers was 13, he underwent multiple Achilles tendon surgeries to straighten his legs. In connection with the surgeries, after the doctor left the room, he quickly glanced at his examination papers, where it was said that he was suffering from FA disease.
&quot;I felt guilty because I was so curious, so I didn&#39;t tell anyone, but when I got home I checked the information about the disease in the library and wrote to the FA association,&quot; he says.
When I got the information from them, I was shocked and in a panic-like state.
I thought I&#39;d be in a wheelchair by the time I was 18 and dead before I turned 25, and in between I&#39;d slowly lose all my ability to function.
I went through this myself and planned my own funeral.
Rodgers says that by the age of 17, he realized that his walking hadn&#39;t deteriorated as much as he had thought and asked his doctor about it.
The doctor just hugged me and said: &quot;baby girl, I don&#39;t think you have this disease, because otherwise you would already be in a wheelchair&quot;.
I think you are suffering from some much less dangerous disease.
Based on some genetic tests, he was diagnosed with CMT.
&quot;When it was explained to me what CMT is, I thought I had been put off,&quot; he says.
