Putin demands that Kyiv open negotiations regarding a new state with eastern Ukraine
Russian President Vladimir Putin demanded on Sunday that the Ukrainian government stop fighting against separatists in the eastern parts of the country and immediately start negotiations on the &quot;statehood&quot; of the breakaway region, Russian news sources say.
His representative Dmitry Peskov later clarified that Putin did not mean that the separatist-controlled region of eastern Ukraine would become part of Russia, but that its position within Ukraine must be reconsidered in order to give the population of the Russian-speaking region the power to defend their own rights and interests.
Putin&#39;s demand for the government in Kiev to negotiate with the pro-Russian rebels as equal partners is in line with his apparent strategy since the violence began five years ago: to help separatists take over the region, effectively forcing the Ukrainian government to grant independence to the newly declared Novorossiya it may turn to Russia instead of the West.
In an interview with the state TV channel Kanava 1, Putin condemned the efforts of the Ukrainian army to recapture the separatist-controlled region of eastern Donetsk and Luhansk, which the separatists seized in March and April after Moscow annexed the Ukrainian Crimean peninsula on March 18.
The Kremlin and the separatists have recently christened the region &quot;Novorossiya&quot;, &quot;New Russia&quot; - a term reminiscent of the days of glory before the Russian superpower revolutions.
According to the Russian news agency Itar-Tassi, Putin said the planned peace talks are an &quot;illusion&quot; as long as Ukrainian politicians campaign for the Oct. 26 parliamentary elections and government forces attack civilians in separatist-held areas.
&quot;We must immediately start extensive negotiations, not only on technical issues, but also on the organization of society and the status of the state of southeastern Ukraine. This way, the interests of the people living there are taken into account,&quot; he says.
Peskov said Putin&#39;s reference to &quot;statehood&quot; is related to a broader independence issue that has been discussed for months with Kiev&#39;s leadership as it tries to allay fears in Russian-speaking regions that their cultural and linguistic rights are under threat.
Only the Ukrainian government can grant the eastern regions the independence they need, says Peskov.
There can be no discussions between Ukraine and Russia on this issue, Peskov says, &quot;because it is not a conflict between Russia and Ukraine, but an internal conflict within Ukraine.&quot;
A Kremlin spokesman&#39;s remarks, aimed at correcting a &quot;misinterpretation&quot; of Putin&#39;s comments, emphasized that the Russian administration is dealing with the separatist rebellion in the eastern regions differently than it did with Crimea, when it effectively seized a region of 2 million people, the majority of whom are ethnic Russians.
It would be significantly more difficult for Moscow to annex even the regions of Donetsk or Luhansk in eastern Ukraine, because most of the 6.5 million people living in the region are not ethnically Russian, and because according to opinion polls before the conflict, the majority of the population supported staying in Ukraine.
Independence, which Russian diplomats have discussed in international forums, would give Ukraine&#39;s local governments the right to negotiate their own trade deals and foreign relations, effectively giving the Kremlin power in the region that connects Russia to Crimea.
The Black Sea peninsula, which was annexed to Russia five months ago, is home to Russia&#39;s main fleet, as well as commercial shipping ports and historical coastal sites.
The area between Russia&#39;s Rostov and Crimea also has mines, factories and smelters that produce vital products for the Russian military.
In his inauguration speech on June 7, Ukrainian President Petro Poroshenko suggested that Ukrainian lawmakers - after new elections - consider constitutional changes to increase the decision-making power of regions outside the core of Ukraine over their own economy and the status of languages.
However, his vision of independence seems to differ sharply from that of the separatists, perhaps armed and fomented by the Kremlin and Moscow.
Putin made his latest demands for the Kiev government to negotiate with the pro-Russian rebels as equal partners, after the rebels made further advances last week after Russian tanks and troops entered eastern Ukraine from a previously peaceful area along the Sea of Azov.
Ukrainian security officials fear that the seizure of the city of Novoazovsk by Russian-backed separatists is the start of a larger effort to seize the entire strategically important coastal region as far as Crimea.
It has led to a massive fortification of the city of Mariupol by civilians and military personnel. With a population of half a million, Mariupol is known as a steel-producing port city located between Novoazovsk and the narrow strip of land leading to the Crimean peninsula.
